ri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">trician to do electrical work in their home.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is anticipated that the proposal will include all licensed Part</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> P Scheme Operators in England and Wales who meet the new scheme requirements in line with DCLG’s timeline, and would lead to the removal from the market place of both existing registers (ElectricSafe Register and the Electrical Safety Register).  We along</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with the above mentioned organisations have written to the Parliamentary Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government setting out our intentions and seeking Government support in this regard</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he combined resources of all electrical CPS provider</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">go a long way to improving awareness of electrical safety in the home and the importance of using com</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">petent, registered electricians.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Awareness of the Building Regulations</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Awareness of the Building Regulations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">requirements </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also remains low.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> surv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ey </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commissioned by ElectricSafe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, highlighted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that only 28.40 per cent of respondents knew what the term “Part P registered electrician” meant and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a worrying 41 per cent of householders </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">were not aware that it was their responsibility to ensure notifiable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">electrical work complies with the Building Regul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tions. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">likely to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">due to the complexity of the different notifications routes available</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the technical nature of the distinction between notifiable an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d non-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">notifiable electrical work (made mo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">complicated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> following the re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cent changes to Part P which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">came into force in April 2013).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We therefore propose that all electrical work which warrants a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">BS7671</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">electrical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">installation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">certificate should re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">quire notification under Part P, and</span><span style="font-fami